According to the multiple regression analysis, IgGGT was positively correlated with alcohol intake (b=0.177, p<0.001), the coronary complexity (b=0.068, p<0.001), and TG (b=0.058, p<0.001), in which alcohol intake and coronary complexity had high correlation coefﬁcients. However, HDL-C levels (b=0.157, p=0.008) and age (b=0.004, p=0.002) were negatively correlated with IgGGT in the CAD group (Table 2).

Serum GGT levels had statistical signiﬁcance (p=0.003) in the triple-vessel disease group when compared with the other groups, demonstrating an increase from single-vessel disease as 23 (16–49) to triple-vessel disease as 30 (20–41.5). In addition, serum HDL-C, apolipoprotein AI, high-sensitivity C reactive protein, hypertension, and diabetes were also significantly higher (p<0.001) in the triple-vessel group. There was no significant difference (p>0.05) in each group concerning serum total cholesterol, triacylglycerol, low-density lipoprotein

With coronary complexity as the dependent variable, multiple-regression analysis revealed that it had a negative correlation with Ig-apolipoprotein AI (b=–2.517, p=0.001), and positive correlations with smoking (b=0.640, p<0.001), IgGGT (b=0.613, p=0.004), Ig high-sensitivity C reactive protein (b=0.320, p<0.001), and hypertension (b=0.286, p<0.026). There was a weak correlation between coronary complexity and age (b=0.037, p<0.001) (Table 3).

